node.title: Should we invite AI into our teams and organisations to improve agility?
node.description:
🤖Should we invite AI into our teams and organisations to improve agility?🤖

Join our thought-provoking debate which will challenge your perceptions and reshape the way you think about AI. Adam, Jas & Ricardo will present compelling arguments exploring potential benefits, challenges and ethical considerations (+some live demos). Will AI enhance agility and help us stay ahead in today's fast paced world? Or does it threaten to disrupt the very essence of human collaboration and creativity?

Bring your burning questions and get ready to cast your vote...*Will you happily welcome AI into your team and organisations by the end of the year to improve agility?*

🕕**AGENDA (GMT)**

17:30-17:40: Kick Off, Introductions + Live Poll

17:40-18:10: 8 minute Lightning Debates - Jas, Adam & Ricardo

18:10-18:30: Panel Discussion, Audience Q&A + Live Poll

**IMPORTANT NOTES**

* I will begin admitting people into the call at 17:30. Before that, you will be on a waitlist to enter.
* Please ensure you're muted at all times to minimise disturbance.
* If you would like to ask a question during the talk, use the Chat.

🗣️**ABOUT THE SPEAKERS**

**Adam Hall**
*Principal technologist, AND Digital*
Adam Hall has worked as a Tech Leader and an Agile Coach since the turn of the millennium. He's passionate about solving human problems with technology and knows that teams working closely together is the way to improve the products we create. Adam is worried about the future and will do anything in his power to ensure that AI adoption is done responsibly and intentionally for the betterment of humanity. If he doesn't, the short slide to robotic domination will be the future that is inherited by his 3 boys. His dog is indifferent to the incoming android apocalypse.

**Jas Singh**
*Director of Agile Coaching, Five AI*
Jas made the switch from disillusioned waterfall battler to agile over 15 years ago and has not looked back. Having built coaching teams with a focus on the system, he now adds his professional coaching skills to support growth in this ever increasingly complex world. The theme of AI is front and centre, as he aids much smarter folk than him in tackling the Autonomous driving problem head on, hoping to be more part of the steering function than a passenger.

**Ricardo Liberato**
*Chief Principal Consultant, Solid Reason*
Ricardo brings a wealth of experience in scaling agile efficiently across various teams and groups, capitalising on lean principles and Gail’s law as the foundation of his work. He is the co-host of the enterprise agility podcast, where he brings his scepticism for the agile industrial complex into the hot topics on enterprise agility. Ricardo is passionate about exploring the intersection between AI technology and agile methodologies to create sustainable, high performing agile teams and agile enterprises. In his spare time he is a software developer building DevOps observability systems for large corporations, pioneering applying natural language processing and large language models to self service observability.

node.title: WOULD YOU LIKE TO KNOW WHAT MAKES A COUPLE COMPATIBLE?
node.description:
From what people tell me, some of them believe that compatibility has to do with having interests in common.

Others believe their partner should have certain specific qualities, such as kindness, a sense of humour, tolerance and good communication.

Having been in two long-term relationships – one very disappointing and the other, my current one, deeply fulfilling – I’ve come to realise that, while both are true to some extent, believe the answer is more complicated.

Take a good sense of humour.

What makes you laugh may leave your partner cold. What is really meant is a SHARED sense of humour.

The same applies to good communication.

For you, good communication may mean being able to share everything; for your partner, it may mean something entirely different.

Join us and find out more.

IF YOU HAVE A PROBLEM GETTING IN, CALL JO ON 07956 568847

node.title: Introduction to NLP and coaching, leading to a certificated qualification
node.description:
“I want to be a coach but…”
“I want to learn how to do NLP but…”
“I’d love to learn about myself and what makes me tick, but …”
Sound familiar? I hear this all the time, and the reasons are usually totally valid, such as:
“I have family commitments”
“I can’t take the time off work to do the course”
“It’s too much information in a short space of time”
There are many more. I totally understand. In order for me to do all of my courses, I had to take annual leave (unpaid in some instances), travel long distances, pay for the course, bed and board, buy food, pay travel and concentrate for long, intense days. This is a huge commitment.
How would it be for you if you could bypass some of these obstacles? If you could undertake an internationally recognised NLP course in the comfort of your own home, and in small, achievable chunks?
NLP is the lead tool in the coaching world. Coaching is an ever-growing profession, and in an era where people are asking more of themselves and often not knowing how to clear the obstacles, we need ways of navigating this territory.
The NLP Diploma is a gateway to the world of human psychology. It offers an introduction to a range of tools and strategies that can move you from a stuck to a more resourceful place.
Its applications are endless! If you want to:
· Set up a coaching business.
· Add tools to your current profession.
· Learn how to manage your own emotions, behaviours and drives.
· Help others to overcome barriers to success.
· Grow and nurture that zest for life.
Then this is for you!
In small, bitesize chunks, I will walk you through the NLP Diploma programme, leading to an internationally recognised qualification from the world’s leading NLP organisation (INLPTA)
For just two and a half hours a week, for 12 weeks, you will learn a wealth of invaluable tools such as:
· How we understand the world
· How we process information
· How you change unwanted behaviour
· How to plan and undertake a coaching session
· How to understand peoples’ outcomes and work towards them
· How to develop linguistic mastery
· How to develop and maintain trust and rapport
And much more!
The first three sessions are FREE, so you can make your mind up about whether it is for you. If it is, then you will continue on a weekly basis for nine more sessions.
On completion of the course, you will obtain your qualification, and will also have accomplished the first four days of the practitioner programme, should you wish to continue on your NLP journey.

node.title: An Agile Coaches Guide to Showing your Value with Bob Galen
node.description:
**Topic:**
An Agile Coaches Guide to Showing Your Value with Bob Galen

**Synopsis:**
Some of the biggest questions facing agile coaches today, whether external consultants/contractors or internal employees; Coaches, ScrumMasters, or leaders are:

* What do you actually do as a coach?
* What difference are you making? What is your value?
* How do I measure your impact?
* Why do I need you as my coach?
* Do I really need your role in my organization?

**Challenging questions to answer, right?**

The premise of this talk is that most coaches are fundamentally unprepared to answer them. That is,many of us struggle to communicate our value, while not appearing self-centered or braggadocios.

In this workshop we will explore how to effectively navigate these value-based questions. We’ll begin in the client entry process and discuss keys for setting up win-win coaching agreements and managing expectations. Next, we’ll explore a wide-variety of approaches for measure agile coaches, their value and their impact. While there is no singular metric, you’ll be exposed to many successful approaches.
And finally, we’ll talk about the importance of brand building and not be shy or reticent in talking about you, which is a problem for so many coaches.

We’ll wrap things up with a Dojo session where we practice strategies for common, value-based situations, so you can leave with new ideas and skills and increased confidence.

**Speaker:**
**Bob Galen** is an Agile Practitioner, Trainer & Coach based in Cary, NC. In this role he helps guide companies and teams in their pragmatic adoption and organizational shift towards agile methods of working. Bob has been doing that since the late 1990s, so he’s deeply experienced.

He is the Director of Agile Practice at Zenergy Technologies, a leading business agility transformation company. Bob is also President and Head Coach at RGCG a boutique agile coaching firm.

Bob regularly speaks at international conferences and professional groups on topics related to agile software development, testing, scaling, and organizational leadership. He is a Certified Enterprise Coach (CEC), Scrum Alliance CAL trainer, and an active member of the Agile & Scrum Alliances.

He’s published four agile-centric books:

* The Three Pillars of Agile Quality and Testing in 2015
* Scrum Product Ownership, 3’rd Edition in 2019
* Agile Reflections in 2012
* Extraordinarily Badass Agile Coaching in 2022.

**Sponsor:**
**Agile Mastery Institute:** Because Mastery Matters.

*AMI is breaking the paradigm of agile certification to offer agile professionals a real pathway towards mastery of their role built around the combination of classroom, coaching and community.*
Find out more: [https://agilemasteryinstitute.com/](https://agilemasteryinstitute.com/)

node.title: Scrum Event & Andrew Hunt (Agile Manifesto Author): Ending the Age of Misery
node.description:
**Scrum Event & Andrew Hunt (Agile Manifesto Author) present: Ending the Age of Misery**

**ABSTRACT:**
The number one problem with software development is thinking that there’s a number one problem.

In fact, there are so many unaddressed problems in software development organizations that instead of the Information Age, you might call this the *Age of Misery.*

Companies large and small fall prey to the joyless enshitification of their business models and users. Developers tire of endless ticketing systems, ponderous practices, and disconnected leadership.

Wouldn’t it be nice to actually get down to work and take comfort in reliable, consistent deliveries that delight the user community?

There’s no single answer, no single solution. But there is a small set of areas that you *can* address to end the *Age of Misery!*

**ABOUT Andy Hunt:**
Andy Hunt is a programmer turned consultant, author and publisher. He’s authored a dozen books, including the best-selling *“The Pragmatic Programmer,”* was one of the 17 authors of the Agile Manifesto and founders of the Agile Alliance, and co-founded the Pragmatic Bookshelf, publishing award-winning and critically acclaimed books for software developers.

He currently writes science fiction [(see conglommora.com)](https://conglommora.com/) and is experimenting with [The GROWS Method®.](https://growsmethod.com/)

**AGENDA:**
18:45 - 19:00 - Event Welcome & Networking
19:00 - 20:00 - Talk
20:00 - 20:15 - Event Questions & Networking
20.15 - Event Ends

SEU:
As a *"Scrum Alliance* *User Group"*, you will earn 1.5 SEUs from this event.
